{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCCN1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O",
      "[H+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine, upon treatment with acid and light (or heat), undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer via a nitrogen-centered radical. The resulting carbon-centered radical then abstracts a chlorine atom from another N-chloroamine molecule. The intermediate 4-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine is then cyclized under basic conditions (e.g., upon workup) to form the final product, N-methylpyrrolidine. This example clearly demonstrates the key remote C-H functionalization and subsequent cyclization to form a five-membered ring, which is characteristic of this reaction.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The reaction involves a specific intramolecular 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer from a carbon to a nitrogen radical, followed by cyclization. The substrate is a simple acyclic N-haloamine. This avoids collision with other named reactions involving intermolecular halogenation, rearrangements of different functional groups (like Hofmann rearrangement of amides), or cyclizations that do not proceed via this specific radical mechanism. The simple aliphatic structure avoids overlap with arene-based reactions."
  }
}
